<h2>How many teaspoons are in a tablespoon?</h2>
<p>
<strong>There are 3 teaspoons in one tablespoon.</strong> An exception to t=
his rule appears in Australia, where one Australian metric tablespoon (20mL=
) equals 4 Australian metric teaspoons (5mL). <sup><a href=3D"https://www.t=
hecalculatorsite.com/cooking/tablespoons-teaspoons.php#ref1" rel=3D"nofollo=
w" title=3D"Go to reference 1">1</a></sup>=20
</p>
<p>
On the basis of the 3:1 conversion factor, we can say the following:
</p>

<strong>How many teaspoons in 1 =C2=BD tablespoons?</strong>

<ul>
 <li>1 =C2=BD tablespoons =3D 4 =C2=BD teaspoons (four and one half)</li>
</ul>

<strong>How many teaspoons in a =C2=BD tablespoon?</strong>

<ul>
 <li>=C2=BD tablespoon =3D 1 =C2=BD teaspoons (one and one half)</li>
</ul>

<strong>How many teaspoons in a =C2=BC tablespoon?</strong>

<ul>
 <li>=C2=BC tablespoon =3D =C2=BE teaspoon (three quarters)</li>
</ul>

<strong>How many teaspoons in a =C2=BE tablespoon?</strong>

<ul>
 <li>=C2=BE tablespoon =3D 2 =C2=BC teaspoons (two and one quarter)</li>
</ul>

<p>
If you want to convert a number of tablespoons into teaspoons, simply multi=
ply the tablespoon number by 3. As an example, if your recipe calls for 4 t=
ablespoons of self-raising flour, you can instead measure out 12 teaspoons =
(4 =C3=97 3 =3D 12).
</p>

